author: {'steamid': '76561198893185241', 'num_games_owned': 18, 'num_reviews': 5, 'playtime_forever': 598, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 598, 'last_played': 1685709997}
review:
Rolling balls,

Panzer Ball is an absolute riot of laughter, and I can't stop smiling from the rolling good time it provides! This game has taken the concept of rolling balls to a whole new level of hilarity, making it an absolute joy to play.

From the moment you start, you'll find yourself immersed in a world where rolling balls is not just a game mechanic but a source of endless amusement. The physics-based gameplay is both challenging and entertaining, as you navigate your spherical friend through a maze of obstacles, pitfalls, and creative environments.

What truly sets Panzer Ball apart is its fantastic sense of humor. The way the balls react to the environment, each other, and even unexpected surprises is nothing short of comedy gold. I found myself chuckling at the absurdity of the situations, especially when my ball went spinning out of control or collided with another ball, creating a chaotic yet delightful chain reaction.

The game's graphics and animation contribute significantly to the overall hilarity. The expressions on the rolling balls are downright funny, and the attention to detail in their movements adds an extra layer of comedic charm. Whether you're bouncing off walls, navigating tricky platforms, or engaging in friendly collisions with other balls, every moment is a potential source of laughter.

Panzer Ball's multiplayer mode takes the hilarity to the next level. Competing against friends in a race to the finish line or engaging in chaotic battles is an absolute blast. The unpredictable nature of the rolling balls ensures that every match is filled with laughter-inducing surprises, making it the perfect game for a fun game night with friends.

In conclusion, Panzer Ball is a shining example of how rolling balls can be the catalyst for side-splitting fun. Its combination of clever level design, engaging gameplay mechanics, and a generous dose of humor make it a must-play for anyone seeking a lighthearted and entertaining gaming experience. Get ready to roll into a world of laughter with Panzer Ball.

author: {'steamid': '76561198970326997', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 10, 'playtime_forever': 1229, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1199, 'last_played': 1690704121}
review:
So this game *used* to be free, apparently it's not anymore. With that said, I was a big fan of this game as a free piece of work, but it still seems incomplete. Call me crazy, but the small handful of levels that exist without steam workshop seems a bit shallow at 15 or so. Yeah if steam workshop is gonna be the main source of content, that's cool, but this game is a bit too small for that to work, as I don't think there's quite enough of a community to keep levels coming out. Thus, I think it can't rely on community levels and probably needs some more levels. Hasn't been updated since like mid 2022 I think?

Yeah anyway I'm rambling. In the state this is in, it shoulda stayed free until there were at least a dozen more of the ~1 min long levels. Even having pretty much done "100%" if you wanna call getting all the stars that, it's not as much as I'd have expected from a game like this, so even if I absolutely enjoy it, I personally wouldn't have been happy had I spent money on the game then had this be the final amount of levels.

review:
*I got this game while it was free*

This is a wildly fun game and it can become addicting trying to beat your personal record. Mechanics are extremely easy to learn, but hard to master. 

The game can be extremely fast paced and the campaign alone is crazy fun. This game deserve a lot more recognition than it currently has. I could see this game reaching masses with the right implementations. Potentially better multiplayer or some sort of cosmetic system that allows the game to be intertwined with Steam Market.

Overall great game and highly recommend.

review:

[h2]Final score: 7/10[/h2]

author: {'steamid': '76561198857639150', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 1, 'playtime_forever': 274, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 226, 'last_played': 1703795816}
review:
I liked that this game allows you to become angry like any other rage games. However, it is untowards of me to put it simply like that. The game is set in an environment that allows one to feel "in between 4 walls"; 
What I mean is, in short, the stages are all cozy and closed, giving a sense of "rooms" as the levels you're supposed to overcome. Giving in to temptation, the player can experience either a deep sense of joy or a fiery fury, depending on how they decide to aprehend the complexities of the level designs. Nonetheless, it is a game in development, as it's the case with everything in life, thus making it always susceptible to improvement. 
The auguments in question could be, per se, the addition of the multiplayer feature, or little power-ups here and there. 
Great game, to say the least. 
So, this is my statement. 
Thank you, everyone, and have a good one.

author: {'steamid': '76561198193708653', 'num_games_owned': 153, 'num_reviews': 26, 'playtime_forever': 1960, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1899, 'last_played': 1654114933}
review: This game should not cost money. I was lucky enough to experience this game when it was free. I wish the developer kept going with this game, it had a community, and it had so much potential. When the editor was released it was amazing, that momentum could have kept the game growing. Instead of the game costing money, there should be skins or a way to donate to the developer. Featured levels, weekly levels, gauntlets, time challenges, this game has so much potential, it's sad to see the developer ignore it. If this game was still free I would fully recommend it, but I just cant recommend as of now.
developer_response:
The game was free.
Then I add level editor.
Then I release.

You have played it for more than 30h.
You come here to complain that it should stay free.

I'm dissapointed in your charl.

author: {'steamid': '76561198339474211', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 301, 'playtime_forever': 100, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 12, 'last_played': 1662143535}
review:
It's quite good and have online MP. The game is dead but there always seems to be at least 1 person in a lobby or you can create your own and wait for people or have friends join. MP has no additional gameplay mechanics but it can be fun to fail with other people or to watch them and learn, just like you would in a CS surfing server.

However the game is quite hard and you will have to enjoy trial & error A LOT. There is almost never any opportunity to recover from a mistake. 1 mistake = back to the start. The campaign missions do have the option to turn on checkpoints  however I feel like this goes against the flow of the game and you should try to reach the finish without checkpoints. There are additional challenges in each level to complete, plus multiple types of leaderboards if you want to speedrun. From what I can see the leaderboards are not ruined by cheaters which is pretty rare these days.

Other features the game has includes workshop support, an in game level editor/creator, VOIP, and the ability to run on a potato PC

Actually it's a really good and complete video game with everything a modern game should have. I suppose the only thing I'd wish for is a MP mode with soccer or something that isn't sweaty.

review:
"Full Controller Support" is a lie, it's about half. Controller seems much more fun than keyboard, but you can't change the default mappings at all and can't edit the camera sensitivity or inversion. Menus and settings are very buggy, the "disable checkpoints" feature just doesn't work, and no sort of replay/ghost features for self or leader board.

Not worth full price, not worth half price. If it had a bit more support it'd be a nice dollar game, but not worth the frustration as it.

author: {'steamid': '76561198037437563', 'num_games_owned': 2147, 'num_reviews': 28, 'playtime_forever': 148, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 148, 'last_played': 1611402497}
review:
At first glance, a decent jumping puzzler. For a while, this impression lasts, with mechanics of the "easy to learn, hard to master" variety. However, some of the later levels are... frustrating (I'm looking at you, Chambers) and as I progressed, my feelings transitioned from "let's play panzerball because it's decent enjoyment" to "let's play panzerball so it's done and I never have to look at it again".

Ultimately, is this game worth the eight hot dogs I could buy instead for its price? No. Unless you're a big parkour fan or happen to catch this game in a big sale, I'd advise you put your money elsewhere.

author: {'steamid': '76561198079487397', 'num_games_owned': 224, 'num_reviews': 16, 'playtime_forever': 445, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 90, 'last_played': 1643164435}
review:
Got this for free, but would have happily paid.  The movement mechanics in this game are insanely fun to mess around with and get good at.  The game really shines when trying to find crazy new routes, jumping off walls and basically ignoring the level lol.

couple of things for the dev:

Needs harder levels.  The mechanics in this game can be really complex (like when going for records and stuff), but unfortunately the level design stops way short of requiring it.  I would love to see some late-game levels that really push the wall jumping / edge jumping to its limits.

Have r be reset from beginning, and another button for restart from checkpoint.  When playing with checkpoints, it would be a nice quality of life thing to be able to go back to the very beginning if you would like.

Also, not quite sure why checkpoints on is a separate mode.  Leaderboards would still be about the same if checkpoints were allowed, because the best scores wouldn't be using them anyway.

This game has a lot of potential.  Definitely will pick it back up whenever it updates.

author: {'steamid': '76561197993203489', 'num_games_owned': 323, 'num_reviews': 4, 'playtime_forever': 2241, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 1617, 'last_played': 1625160641}
review:
Panzer ball is a simple marble racing game.  There are a small handful of maps with the game.  The main drive of it is something like Trackmania; racing on a map over and over again to work on your time.

Currently, the game has a small but active community that go pretty hard on the leaderboards.  The game creator just added a level editor, and already people are coming up with some really cool levels!

If you are unsure, watch Northerlion's let's play on youtube and you will get the vibe in 5 minutes.  For me, I have had fun building levels and lazily joining a server and grinding away at times before bed!

author: {'steamid': '76561198032744129', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 59, 'playtime_forever': 786, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 69, 'last_played': 1603999504}
review: If you're a fan of speedrunning, grinding runs/routes to climb a leaderboard, you're likely going to love Panzer Ball.  Controls feel good, maps are interesting so far, and just overall feels like it's going to be a great game.  Mechanics are mostly simple on the surface, but as with any game like this, the application of the mechanics and timing become extremely complicated so there's a lot to learn, refine, and improve on.  It's free right now in early access so give it a try, download is small and it's a lot of fun to challenge yourself for better times.

review:
So far it's a short but very enjoyable experience. It scratches that same "I can do a little better here" itch that Trackmania has, but in a different way. It has a learning curve, but in a easy-to-learn-hard-to-master way.

 I am really excited for new maps, and a map editor would be a massive boon for this game.

author: {'steamid': '76561198014840057', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 42, 'playtime_forever': 349, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 297, 'last_played': 1594705005}
review:
There's a lot to like about this game, especially for a free game.

It's simple, fun, has some cool strategies, leaderboards, everything you need for a simple little jump puzzle game. But it has one major flaw, one that made me and my friends all quit upon learning about it.


Edit: [b]Your framerate influences gameplay directly.[/b]
(See video in comments for update; Currently being investigated by dev)

Upon getting a couple top 100 spots on a few maps and enjoying pushing our strategies, we all got stuck trying to hit the speed needed to needed to make a sweet jump on one of the maps. After a failed 30 minute session we resolved to look into some videos of the top runners, and realized they were purposely running at 30fps. Low and behold, the exact same strategies that struggled to get us to 450 speed were now reliably breaking 650, and the jump became possible.

I just cannot recommend a game that pushes you to cap your fps to compete, especially at something so low. Would certainly be down to come back if this was updated.
developer_response:
The physics should always run at the same tick frequency. If frame-rate is below desired FPS it does some sub-steps to catch up. Perhaps something is going wrong during the sub-step force calculation.

As far as I know most if not all world records are above 60 fps ( leaderboards tracks some stats such as frame-rate ) but perhaps in some maps the 30 FPS trick/bug does give an advantage.

If you have time and are willing, it'd help me a ton if you could record the section where 30-fps gives a speed boost you would not be able to get otherwise. That way I can try and recreate the issue and then fix it :)

If you do have a clip of it, feel free to post here or on the discord, so we can discuss/fix it. Thanks!

author: {'steamid': '76561198304127021', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 56, 'playtime_forever': 46, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 46, 'last_played': 1593155960}
review: I really do like the wall jumping and the course designs, but that's as far as I can compliment it. Really, the physics are just too janky in my opinion. If you really want to make surf maps, you really gotta have surf movement, as in being able to strafe in the air a little bit and just have more general friction. The gameplay is at it's best when you're jumping from wall to wall or instantly jumping off the ground but as soon as you try to land somewhere it just falls apart. Going for some of the letters made me realize the slipperiness of the ball and the inability to correct your air momentum left or right really hinders your overall movement. I know it's a marble game and reliant on physics but even then there just isn't any real weight to the ball, it feels like ice physics almost, making it so any cool thing you want to do would be wildly inconsistent to pull off, not because you're not smart enough to do it but because you can't predict the controls or use them ideally.

review:
For newbies, this game is called Panzer Ball, an exciting game about being a ball and using very fun physics to platform your way around several maps. For a beta, I'd like to say this game is amazing. There are little to no flaws and the newly added VOID levels add tons of new platforming experiences. Definitely worth the time to play with friends. Or, if you don't have any friends, you can still play the CAMPAIGN for challenges in speed running, collecting, and even just being able to clear the level itself! Are you a Panzer Ball champ?! Go ahead and download to see!

NOTICE - As of this review, the game is free. Statements may be invalid if creator adds a price tag in the near future...

author: {'steamid': '76561197960404906', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 7, 'playtime_forever': 64, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 50, 'last_played': 1592160115}
review:
[quote][url=store.steampowered.com/curator/7279/]Follow our curators page [b]Climbers-Germany[/b] if you like this review or like to play more movement based games[/url][/quote]

Panzer Ball is a fast paced bhop game in early access and is free to play.
Where other mods are failing to get a competition going on. Panzer Ball is fixing this with integrated Steam Leaderboards.
The only down side of it, you can't watch the run of the loaderboards for now (hopefully this will be a feature in a later version)
Spectating someone felt laggy maybe that could be an issue from the server hoster or the player itself.
But didn't ruin the gameplay for us.

----

Coming from the cs1.6 movement scene, i got every fast attracted to the game while playing it.
The movement felt quite similiar but hard to handle because we are playing a Ball.
Sometimes we have to avoid lasers or trying to drive the ball thru a narrow path.

With the multiplayer component, you can even invite your jumping friends to have a lovely, laughable challegene.

We from Climbers-Germany will for sure follow the further developement of this game, because it we like the concept.

A short review but everything is said with the actual version as of 06-14-2020
[quote]The game is free in the actual early access version. So i did not receive any compensation for writing this review. The review is based on my own opinion and were not influenced in any way.[/quote]

author: {'steamid': '76561198071661056', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 31, 'playtime_forever': 179, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 179, 'last_played': 1591784024}
review:
I could see this becoming a new fix for those who love CSGO surfing. Really high skill movement "get to the finish fast" game where you play as a marble that can charge its jump. The game also runs great! Think the only thing the game needs is some sort of staying power.

Love the idea of a ranked mode that puts you in a lobby on one of the maps or even a procedurally generated one with other players for 30 minutes. Bonus points to whoever finishes the course first, but the real winner is crowned when the time runs out. Those with the fastest course times rank up, the others lose. Seems like a simple enough way (minus the procedurally generated stuff) to encourage people to play more.

Either way, really fun game to sink time into, plus it's free so you might as well try it. Speaking of which, @ the dev team, put some cosmetics in so we can buy them to support you!

review:
I haven't even played for 30 minutes yet, and I love the game! For being mainly a one person project, I think it's coming along great, and from what I've read in the developer's notes I can't wait for the full release. To me, this game feels like a combination of Portal and either mini golf or those marble racing games. 

If you are into puzzles or 3D platformers, I definitely recommend this game!

author: {'steamid': '76561198111779617', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 14, 'playtime_forever': 19891, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 6132, 'last_played': 1658645740}
review:
Great game. Movement feels smooth, online is easy to use (no private lobbies atm), and a map creator is in the works. Active discord run by the dev who is involved with the community.

It has some physics quirks. Sometimes you hit the ground, bounce strangely and lose all speed. Your fps has a slight effect on how your ball interacts with the map (e.g. 60 fps feels a little slippery for me, but 144 is fine), though in my experience one can do perfectly fine competing for top times at 144. These issues generally don't affect gameplay too much.

Overall a great indie speedrunning platformer. Big thanks to NorthernLion for showcasing it.

review: Truly impressive and highly addictive, this game showcases great physics and a very exciting amount of potential. It is punishingly difficult but every error is your own, each time you are sent back to the start you will be more determined to reach the end. It had me punching the air and screaming "YEAH B**CH" like Jesse Pinkman when I beat my PB. If the developer can add in some more multiplayer game modes like racing or collecting letters, or even a battle mode where players must keep moving and try to eliminate each other, this will make for a truly competitive multiplayer experience. It is already one of steam's hidden gems and made all the more impressive by the fact that it is mainly created by one person.

author: {'steamid': '76561198244925166', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 8, 'playtime_forever': 712, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 75, 'last_played': 1684117216}
review:
Hola!!! La verdad es que el juego es super divertido! super frenetico y bastante dificil! 
Creo que estaria genial agregarle ciertas cosas que creo que serian muy interesantes:

*Diversidad de tem√°ticas en cuanto a niveles (Niveles en los que los obstaculos no sean solo lasers especificamente) Creo que si le podrian agregar diferentes tematicas a los niveles seria mucho mas interesante y/o adictivo. Ej: Tematicas de hielo (Pinches decorativos que a su vez te maten) 

*Acomodar las dificultades para los jugadores (En el caso de que no sea de su inter√©s agregar tematicas) Creo que seria bastante importante ordenar los niveles en cierta forma en la que no halla un salto dem√°ciado grande de dificultad para jugadores nuevos, en los niveles de lasers de el 1 al 3 hay una diferencia bastante grande de dificultad. 

*¬øSkins?: Me parece que el juego da bastantes posibilades a skins, particulas de movimiento o edici√≥n de la pelota (Colores y etc) O quiz√° les servir√≠a mas adelante agregar skins para las personas que donan. 

*Tener la opci√≥n de jugar los mapas en modo "Carrera" para poder jugar contra amigos, creo que seria demaciado, DEMACIADO, divertido (Lo menciono por que es como lo est√°bamos jugando con mis amigos) intent√°bamos hacer constantemente el record de tiempo para superarnos, y el modo carrera agregar√≠a tensi√≥n y mas momentos de risa. 

* Y por ultimo pero lo MAS IMPORTANTE DE TODO. UNA "WORKSHOP" no estoy muy seguro de como funciona para agregar workshop, pero si pudieran hacerlo, seria un juego extremadamente adictivo, con posibilidades muy muy muy grandes, que cada usuario pueda crear su nivel, a su propio estilo, con su propia dificultad, creo que tendria un gran exito y le daria muchisimo mas entretenimiento a todos los usuarios, creo que es un detalle muy importante que podrian tener en cuenta. 

Cabe destacar que no menciono puntos negativos por que realmente es bastante interesante el juego, no encuentro muchos errores, de momento es todo lo que dir√©. 

¬°Continuen con el desarrollo de este juego! Puede ser increible.

author: {'steamid': '76561197994049222', 'num_games_owned': 1319, 'num_reviews': 163, 'playtime_forever': 73, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 23, 'last_played': 1603590777}
review:
I'm going to be real with you, this already does so many things better than comparable marble/ball games by the sheer virtue of how well it controls. It‚Äôs not just Monkey Ball with great jumps, it‚Äôs not just Marble Skies with wall jumps. From using platform edges for a boosted edge jump to charging up a jump for extra height at any time, everything works together. Your ball is just the right kind of sticky to hold on to walls without feeling glued on while rolling on them. Their velocity and speed work just right for these required maneuvers.

Beyond that, Panzer Ball also understands the philosophy behind Super Meat Boy‚Äôs respawning: You‚Äôre a platformer, so respawning needs to be *quick*. Hearing FALL OUT in Monkey Ball or countdown in Marble Skies makes repetition and learning just frustrating. Panzer Ball shows what killed you and in a split second, you‚Äôre back where you need to be.

As for criticisms, I‚Äôve got two simple ones. First, make the respawning even quicker, or make it an option or a slider or something. Despite how fast I respawn, pressing the respawn button myself should put me back even quicker. I don‚Äôt need to see myself poof in a bundle of smoke when pressing it, I need to be right at the start already.

Allow us to use the right bumper to navigate the menu. The A or RB button both function as the jump button, but the latter frees up your thumb to control the camera. Having to not move my index finger to go through the menu would only speed up that much more.

Also‚Ä¶ Where‚Äôs the exit button? I tried to leave to post this review, having backed out fully, and it wouldn‚Äôt let me leave. Had to pull out that good ol‚Äô Alt+F4 to exit. It‚Äôs a small thing, but a vital one nonetheless.

In case you were wondering, yes these two criticisms are mere nitpicks. For a free Early Access game, Panzer is a great marble game that scratches the itch just right with a different aesthetic and a new spin on the genre. Game like this, I‚Äôd easily deck 5 bucks for it, no questions asked. Probably even ten when it comes out of Early Access. You did good, LODZERO!

author: {'steamid': '76561197994701612', 'num_games_owned': 0, 'num_reviews': 24, 'playtime_forever': 445, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 123, 'last_played': 1629723876}
review:

author: {'steamid': '76561198055319056', 'num_games_owned': 503, 'num_reviews': 63, 'playtime_forever': 272, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 250, 'last_played': 1650054849}
review:
Panzerball - Ein Spiel welches ein "Was stellst du dich so an" in ein "BEIM N√ÑCHSTEN MAL WO ICH VERKACKE BEI√ü ICH IN DIE SCHEI√ü TISCHPLATTE" innerhalb von Sekunden ver√§ndern kann.

Das Spiel ist abwechslungsreich, mal was neues, Kostenlos und sehr sch√∂n anzusehen:
Das Spiel stellt einen vor die Herausforderung, mit Freunden gemeinsam einen Ball durch ein sehr sch√∂n designetes Level  so schnell es geht durchzujagen. Dabei werden immer wieder neue Rekorde, sowie Freundschaften gebrochen und es entsteht somit ein wunderbarer Wettkampf.

Die Grafik ist sehr sch√∂n anzusehen und man merkt wie viel Liebe sich in den Leveldesigns niederschl√§gt.
Zwar sind die Elemente aus denen das Level besteht meist "Grauer Umgebung & Gl√ºhenden Hitzest√§ben", aber daf√ºr sind die Levels selber immer neu und abwechslungsreich aufgebaut, was den Spielspa√ü und vorallem die Herausforderung aufrechterh√§lt.

An und f√ºr sich kann man nicht mehr zu diesem Spiel sagen, au√üer, dass es vorallem jetzt in der Coronazeit ein wunderbarer Zeitvertreib mit Freunden und Kollegen ist, man somit etwas mehr in Kontakt kommt und gemeinsam Spa√ü (und Wutanf√§lle) erleben kann.

Das Spiel bekommt von mir folgende Bewertung:

Spa√ü: 10/10
Leveldesign: 9/10
Schwierigkeitsgrad: 10/10
Wiederspielwert: 10/10
Spa√üfaktor mit Freunden: 20/10
-----
GESAMT: 59/50
----
FAZIT: Daumen hoch f√ºr dieses Spiel. Freue mich sehr auf die weiteren Inhalte, welche noch kommen. F√ºr ein Early Access Spiel sehr Umfangreich und sehr stabil. Keine Abst√ºrze oder Verbindungsprobleme. Ich bin sehr auf die kommenden Inhalte gehyped und werde das Spiel auf jeden Fall weiterhin verfolgen.

author: {'steamid': '76561198352742768', 'num_games_owned': 159, 'num_reviews': 2, 'playtime_forever': 482, 'playtime_last_two_weeks': 0, 'playtime_at_review': 247, 'last_played': 1622571172}
review:
Disclaimer: This review was written at a very early point of its development, when it as free. However, it is really fun and well worth the $4.

Anyways: --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Very fun game if you have some friends willing to have some fun and some time to kill. After about 2h you're already getting close to the wr times and honestly it's really fun.

I don't know why the game has PANZER in its name though. But that's the developer's choice and hey, it's fun just shouting "LET'S PLAY [b]PANZERBALL[/b]" really loud at your friends in discord.

This is the perfect game for a situation such as the current crisis. Can't go out and play some [i]whatever[/i] with your friends? Just go on discord and f**k up each other in this game. Friendships have broken, some have formed and some rediscovered.

The only few things I would change are the following:
- The main menu from where you can actually set up yourself to play the game is only accesable after 2 
button presses
- There are no private lobbies, so random strangers can just join your party and keep you from actually 
achieving anything
- The current amount of levels is really low (3), but it's just an alpha so it's not really a negative. But a suggestion for the game would be to introduce a custom level editor and with it steam workshop integration. But as stated above, this is just an alpha at the point that I'm writing this review so expect things to change, because a level editor would just perfectly fit into this game.

review:
Marble Madness if it were a hardcore platformer. It's simple to pick up, plenty of room for high skill players to get competitive, fun, and free. No reason to pass on this one. Plus the multiplayer lets you watch others biff it. Good for a laugh.

Only thing it needs is a map editor and a variety of fun multiplayer modes.

review: If you're an early starting speed runner, this is where you want to be. This game requires a high, but simple, skill level and understanding of aerodynamics and keeping momentum.
